    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Capalaba sits approximately twenty-five kilometres east of the Brisbane CBD, occupying a central position as the major service hub for Brisbane's eastern residential corridor. The suburb draws families who have made a deliberate decision to move east, prioritising generous residential blocks, schooling options, and the self-contained day-to-day lifestyle that Capalaba's commercial centre, health services, and community facilities provide. Buyers who choose Capalaba in 2026 have generally been comparing the eastern corridor thoroughly and have concluded that the suburb's combination of space, schools, and practical amenity represents the best available option at their budget. Understanding that buyer, and running a campaign that speaks directly to what they are looking for, is how sellers in Capalaba get the best result from the market.</p>

      <p>The Capalaba Park shopping centre and the surrounding retail and health services precinct make the suburb genuinely self-contained in a way that most comparable outer-eastern suburbs are not. For a family making the move to the eastern corridor, the prospect of having a full-service retail and health centre within easy distance of home is a quality-of-life asset that shows up in the buyer's comparison of suburb options. It is worth communicating this practical advantage clearly in your campaign rather than assuming that buyers who are already comparing the corridor will have connected the dots on their own.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Capalaba</h2>
      <p>The dominant buyer in Capalaba is the family that has made a deliberate decision to move east for space, schooling, and a self-contained suburban lifestyle. These buyers have typically been comparing the eastern corridor across several months, visiting Manly West, Belmont, Alexandra Hills and Capalaba, and have concluded that Capalaba offers the right combination of block size, school access, and everyday amenity at the price point they are working with. That buyer arrives at your open home having already done their research on the suburb, and their main task is deciding whether your specific property is the right fit.</p>

      <p>Capalaba State College is a specific draw for families who want a Prep to Year 12 pathway without the complexity of transitioning children between a primary and a separate secondary school. For parents who are weighing this consideration, the presence of the college in the suburb simplifies a decision that would otherwise require comparing primary and secondary catchments separately. When a buyer has resolved that question through Capalaba, their focus at an open home is on the property rather than the schooling question.</p>

      <p>First-home buyers represent a consistent buyer segment in Capalaba, particularly for the more modestly sized properties and townhouses within the suburb. These buyers are often comparing Capalaba with Belmont, Wynnum West, and Alexandra Hills as the most accessible options in the eastern corridor, and Capalaba's combination of amenity and block size makes it competitive within that group.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Capalaba</h2>
      <p>Block size is the most fundamental value driver in Capalaba. The families who choose this suburb over a closer-in address are making a deliberate trade: less proximity to the CBD for more outdoor space. Properties that make the most of that outdoor space, that present the backyard as genuinely functional and private, and that give buyers a clear picture of how the block can support the family lifestyle they are moving east to achieve, are consistently the properties that attract the most competitive buyer interest.</p>

      <p>Proximity to Capalaba State College and the Capalaba Park shopping precinct is a secondary value driver that shows up most clearly when comparing properties within the suburb. Homes within walking distance of the college entrance or within easy reach of the shopping centre precinct occupy a different buyer consideration than properties that require a drive for every school and retail interaction. The difference may not be dramatic in comparable sales, but it is present and worth understanding before you set a pricing strategy.</p>

      <p>Street character also matters in Capalaba. The suburb has areas with mature street tree cover, established gardens, and a settled residential feel that contrast with more recently developed pockets or areas closer to the commercial corridors. Buyers who have been comparing the suburb's internal geography will pay attention to these distinctions, and a seller who understands their property's position in that internal hierarchy is better placed to price accurately and to direct their presentation effort where it will make the most difference.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing your Capalaba home for sale</h2>
      <p>The buyers who target Capalaba are looking for a family home that functions well and delivers the outdoor space that is the primary reason they are moving east. Preparation that focuses on the outdoor spaces, addresses the practical condition items that undermine buyer confidence, and presents the home as genuinely ready to move into will make the most difference to both the quality of the buyer pool and the competitive atmosphere of your campaign. A well-maintained Capalaba home with a functional, well-presented backyard and an outdoor entertaining area that looks usable is meeting the buyer's core expectation for what this suburb should deliver.</p>

      <p>Interior presentation matters too, particularly in the living areas and kitchen where first impressions are formed and where buyers are assessing whether the home's floor plan and condition match what a move-in-ready property should look like. The buyers comparing the eastern corridor at this price point are practical people making a practical decision, and a home that presents as clean, maintained, and genuinely ready for a family to occupy will outperform one that asks buyers to discount for work they will need to do.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Best time to sell in Capalaba</h2>
      <p>Capalaba follows the broader Brisbane seasonal pattern, with autumn (late February through May) and spring (September through November) as the two windows that produce the strongest campaign conditions for family properties. Autumn is particularly consistent for the eastern corridor because family buyers who have been comparing the suburb options east of the city through the summer period arrive in February and March with clear intent, an informed budget, and in many cases a school-year-start timeline that creates genuine urgency. A well-prepared Capalaba property that launches in late February or March will typically face a smaller competing stock profile than the same property launched in October, and the buyers present in the market in that window tend to be more focused and less distracted by the range of listings that spring brings.</p>

      <p>Spring remains a sound window for a well-prepared and correctly priced property. The higher volume of buyers in September and October compensates for the increased competing stock, and a property that stands out clearly from its comparable listings will attract competitive interest in either season. The practical guidance is that sellers who can launch in late February or early March should seriously consider it. Those who have a spring timeline should invest in the preparation work that makes their property the obvious choice within its competing stock group.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long does it take to sell in Capalaba</h2>
      <p>Well-presented Capalaba homes, accurately priced against recent comparable sales for the specific street position and property type, typically sell within 30 to 45 days. The suburb's broad family buyer base and its role as the eastern corridor's hub mean that genuine buyer interest is consistent throughout the year and does not depend as heavily on seasonal windows as some more niche suburb markets. The buyers who target Capalaba are practical and motivated when the right property appears at a realistic price. Correct pricing against current comparables is the most controllable factor in campaign length: an overpriced property in Capalaba will sit and accumulate days on market, while a well-priced one draws the prepared buyer pool to a decisive outcome.</p>

